post_cb({"3858490": {"ParentId": "3858470", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>Yes, you're dereferencing a null pointer when you do <code>*pointer</code> in line 2.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "149392", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "3858490", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2010-10-04T19:37:04.927", "LastActivityDate": "2010-10-04T19:37:04.927"}, "3858485": {"ParentId": "3858470", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "3", "Body": "<p>Yes.  </p>\n<pre><code>double *pointer = 0;    // init `pointer` to a NULL pointer value\ndouble &amp;value = *pointer; // dereference it\n</code></pre>\n<p>The standard specifically speaks to this situation - from 8.3.2/4 \"References\":</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_3858470_3858485_0\">A reference shall be initialized to\n  refer to a valid object or function.\n  [Note: in particular, a null reference\n  cannot exist in a well-defined\n  program, because the only way to\n  create such a reference would be to\n  bind it to the \u201cobject\u201d obtained by\n  dereferencing a null pointer, which\n  causes undefined behavior. As\n  described in 9.6, a reference cannot\n  be bound directly to a bit-field. ]</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "12711", "LastEditorUserId": "12711", "LastEditDate": "2010-10-04T19:47:01.067", "Id": "3858485", "Score": "6", "CreationDate": "2010-10-04T19:36:46.457", "LastActivityDate": "2010-10-04T19:47:01.067"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_3858470_3858485_0": {"section_id": 3222, "quality": 0.9411764705882353, "length": 32}}, "n3337": {"so_3858470_3858485_0": {"section_id": 3096, "quality": 0.9705882352941176, "length": 33}}, "n4659": {"so_3858470_3858485_0": {"section_id": 3979, "quality": 0.9411764705882353, "length": 32}}}, "3858470": {"CommentCount": "8", "ViewCount": "165", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "224671", "CreationDate": "2010-10-04T19:34:55.510", "LastActivityDate": "2010-10-04T19:47:01.067", "Title": "C++ standard question", "AcceptedAnswerId": "3858485", "LastEditDate": "2010-10-04T19:40:42.673", "Id": "3858470", "Score": "0", "Body": "<p>should the following result in undefined behavior?</p>\n<p>should value of pointer2 be NULL?</p>\n<pre><code>double *pointer = 0;\ndouble &amp;value = *pointer;\ndouble *pointer2 = &amp;value;\n</code></pre>\n", "Tags": "<c++>", "OwnerUserId": "206328", "AnswerCount": "2"}});